### User Story

As a user, I want to stay logged into the app so that I can easily use it without logging on.

### Description

[comment]: # (Feature or Bug? i.e Type: Bug)
*Type*: Bug

[comment]: # (Describe the feature you would like, or briefly summarise the bug and what you did, what you expected to happen, and what actually happens. Sections below)
*Summary*: When using Status it can be very frustrating to be logged out of the app on a regular basis. For example, I can receive a push notification, tap it, and go to read the message but I'm blocked with a login screen. 

#### Expected behavior
As a user expect that the app is always accessible without logging in.
#### Actual behavior
As a user I am frequently logged out. 

### Reproduction
Restart the app and the user is logged out.

In the future it might be nice for the user to set the authentication level from a Privacy section in Settings. Eg always require login, or require if inactive for X minutes. Also will be nice to have touch/faceID integrated at some stage.
Edited and factored this issue into two to keep scope limited: https://github.com/status-im/status-react/issues/2872
@chadyj @oskarth should user be logged out when the app process is killed? Other apps like Messanger keep user logged in. It's really annoying when I'm logged but I didn't expect it.

@lukaszfryc I can't think of any reason why a user would be logged within normal use over a few hours. The behaviour of other apps like you suggest is expected here.  

I've seen some web apps give an option to the user like "keep me logged in", etc. This could be an option in the future to give users granular control, but for now we can keep them logged in until they log out.

One concern here, of course, is that we will have to cache both account ID and password somewhere on a device in that case.
So, 
1. We need to use OS-recommended provided secure storage for that:
    - iOS: Keychain
    - Android: ???
2. We need to encrypt the password with some key when storing it (preferably, derived from something unique for the app installation + salt);
3. We need someone with a proper security background to review the implementation details 😄
That is all important because the credentials aren't revokable. If someone steals this auth data, the user account will be compromised forever, right?
One more thing to think about: requiring to always enter a password will lead to people choosing poor passwords that are easy to type.

Great points @mandrigin.
Once these underlying issues are addressed we can also explore enhanced improvements like touch/faceid!

Having to use Touch or Face ID so often maybe really frustrating. Imagine clicking a notification, having to authenticate and then waiting for the app to log you in. It's time consuming. 

I wonder if there is a way to keep the app always ready to use and only require authentication for crucial activities like transactions / wallet.

💯 
we need to split the app into a wallet and a messenger.
they have very different requirements and expectations on security mechanisms

It seems that the only way to solve this issue is to restore state after crash so that user don't have to enter password again. In most cases app is purged when being suspended on iOS because system needs more memory, and as far as i can say it can happen even to application which consumes ~2MB being suspended. So better to focus on restoring state after termination (and on all security related consequences) . @chadyj @mandrigin p.s.: https://developer.apple.com/documentation/uikit/uiapplicationdelegate/1623111-applicationwillterminate can be useful on iOS
applicationWillTerminate(_:) - UIApplicationDelegate | Apple Developer Documentation

> Imagine clicking a notification, having to authenticate and then waiting for the app to log you in. It's time consuming.

Not only that, it will take away any value from improvements like https://github.com/status-im/status-react/issues/3451 on anything other than very high-end devices (i.e. 6GB+ RAM), since the app won't be able to access the user's account after having been evicted from memory.
